<h2 id="extreme-programmingxp익스트림-프로그래밍">Extreme Programming(XP)(익스트림 프로그래밍)</h2>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>It is kind of practices(관행)</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>One of the well-known Agile process</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Rarely does a team follow XP strictly now</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Each practice could be adjusted for a given team/project</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<h2 id="the-12-xp-practices익스트림-프로그래밍-관습">The 12 XP Practices(익스트림 프로그래밍 관습)</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>The Planning Game:</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>Use user stories and story points at the beginning of each iteration to plan</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><strong>Whole Team(a.k.a. On-site customer)</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>Everyone(from business to coders to QA to customer) is part of one team and is co-located as much as possible to promote cohesion</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><strong>Sustainable Pace(a.k.a. The 40-hour work week)</strong>
    <ul>
      <li><u>Team members that work too much burn out quicker and are much more likely to introduce defects into the system.</u></li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><strong>Small Releases</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>Get customer feedback early and often to prevent building the wrong solution</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><strong>Coding Standards</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>Following good coding standards and naming mitigates the need for extensive documentation</li>
      <li>The code shold always be understandable and an artifact unto itself</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><strong>Pair Programming</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>An early inverstment in learning how to pair yields significant results in reducing the number of defects injected into a system</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><strong>Test-Driven Development</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>Test first, then write the code that passes the test</li>
      <li>Make tests automated and add them to the overall code base</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><strong>Refactor Mercilessly</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>Continuously imporve your codebase and don’t leave anything stagnant</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><strong>Collective Code Ownership</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>No one ‘owns’ any part of the system</li>
      <li>Anyone can update any part of the code when needed</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><strong>Continuous Integration</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>Constantly build the code</li>
      <li>When code is checked in, run all tests and rebuild</li>
      <li>Always have a working build</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><strong>Simple Design</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>Build the simplest thing that works</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><strong>Metaphor Over Architecture</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>Have a narrative / description that can be used to communicate design decisions</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><strong>Stand-Up Meeting</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>The start of every workday begins with a meeting in which all team members must stand in circle, giving updates and what they will work on that day</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Why do they stand? To prevent the meeting from going too long…</p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h2 id="scrum">Scrum</h2>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Another Agile Methodology</strong></p>
  </li>
  <li>특정 개발 언어나 방법론에 의존적이지 않으며, 제품 개발 뿐만 아니라 일반적인 프로젝트 관리에도 사용 가능한 프로세스 프레임워크이다</li>
  <li>작은 주기(Sprint)로 개발 및 검토를 하며, 효율적인 협업 방법을 제공함.</li>
</ul>

<p><img src="https://seungeonK.github.io/assets/images/scrum.jpg" alt="" /></p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Focuses on</strong>:
    <ul>
      <li>Simplicity</li>
      <li>ANY complex project(not just software)</li>
      <li>Constant feedback(both with team and customer)</li>
      <li>Sprint iterations always end with a potentially shippable product</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><strong>What’s Sprint?</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>Sprint is a dedicated amount of time and say “check point”</li>
      <li>Over that time frame, see what we can do, what the hightest priority feature</li>
      <li>At the end of the scrum, you should have ‘something’ working.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><strong>Applying Scrum to CS3240</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>Will be using Scrum for our projects</li>
      <li>Will create a product backlog based on the project you pick</li>
      <li>During each sprint, your team will choose user stories off the backlog to work on</li>
      <li>Each week, your team will have a stand-up meeting, demo to the customer(TA), and plan the next sprint</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

